==English==

===Etymology===
Greek μουοφυδίής, “single nature”

====Noun====
'''monophysism'''
#A [[heresy]] which holds that Jesus Christ has one nature that is both human nature and divine at the same time, as opposed to the orthodox view that Christ has two natures, both fully man and fully God, and is co-eternal and co-substantial with the Father. The Church of Alexandria in Egypt was considered [[monophysite]], and therefore [[heterodox]] instead of [[orthodox]]. The doctrine of [[incarnation]] that is now commonly agreed upon - that Christ was both fully human and fully God - was formalized as the [[Nicene Creed]] in the 4th century in Nicea.

====Related terms====
[[monophysite]]
*Monophysites are called [[copt]]s [[Copt]]s in Egypt.
*Monophysites are called [[jacobite]]s [[Jacobite]]s in Syria and Palastine.

